The paper deals with fast algorithms for computing pairwise interactions between a large set of points in high dimensions, which is a common problem in numerical analysis and scientific computing. The use of treecodes and fast multipole methods suggests that the paper may belong to the numerical analysis (cs.NA) or scientific computing (cs.SC) categories. The focus on low-rank approximations and randomized algorithms suggests that the paper may also belong to the data structures (cs.DS) or computational geometry (cs.CG) categories. Finally, the use of kernel functions and their applications in physics and data analysis suggests that the paper may also belong to the machine learning (cs.SI) category.
